         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">14/6/84. ¶  ¶ The addition of Hakea Baxteri to the S.A. Flora is very interesting, dear Professor, showing that many W.A plants you will have to call yet your own in S.A. ¶  ¶ It is very generous of y...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">84.06.14</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Ralph Tate</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Barr Smith Library, University of Adelaide, SA.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">14/6/84.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The addition of <name key="Hakea%20Baxteri">Hakea Baxteri</name> to the S.A. Flora is very interesting, dear Professor, showing that many W.A plants you will have to call yet your own in S.A.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is very generous of you, to invite me to your new estate near Nairne;<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>SA.</p>
               </note> and I beg to thank you and your kind Lady for the offered hospitality, which some day I may have the happiness to accept, and heightened by botanic wanderings in the environs with you.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This invitation brings me back 30 years and more, when a highly gifted and noble-minded sister of mine<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bertha Doughty, née Müller.</p>
               </note> long passed away since was staying as a friend with the late Mrs Smillie, the mother of the then Advocate General of South Australia.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>William Smillie.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Later the widow of Mr Smillie lived at Nairne, after having educated her beautiful young daughters in Germany and France. But alas! the young Ladies, who had inhered<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>inherited?</p>
               </note> the tendency to Consumption from their father, fell both early victims to Phthisis; and the sorrowing mother lives now childless in Florence, retaining still as a source of income, so I believe, the Nairne property.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Let me advise you, to sow part of your property with <name key="Acacia%20decurrens">Acacia decurrens</name>. It grows much faster than A. pycnantha, has a bark quite as rich in tannin and much heavier. Of course, you will know, that A. decurrens is a much larger tree. Fresh seeds you would get cheaply and correct to name from Mr F. Abbott, Director of the bot. Garden of Hobart, who would guard against your getting seeds of <name key="Acacia%20dealbata">Acacia dealbata</name>. See "select plants<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B81.01.04. On p. 4 of this work, M cautions that the bark of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">A. dealbata </seg>is 'much thinner and greatly inferior … in quality' to that of<seg style="font-style: italic; "> A. decurrens.</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.8264in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS ends without valediction at the bottom of the fourth and final page on the sheet.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
